#let images = (
  "13-1": (
    caption: [The constituents of blood. Blood cells become packed at the bottom of the test tube when whole blood is centrifuged, leaving the fluid plasma at the top of the tube. Red blood cells are the most abundant formed elements, accounting for about 45% of the blood volume (the hematocrit). White blood cells and platelets form a thin, light-colored buffy coat between the packed red blood cells and the plasma.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-2": (
    caption: [A scanning electron micrograph of red blood cells. The red blood cells are clinging to a hypodermic needle, showing their characteristic biconcave disc shape. This shape maximizes the surface area-to-volume ratio, facilitating gas exchange.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-3": (
    caption: [The blood cells and platelets. The figure shows different types of white blood cells including granular leukocytes (neutrophils, eosinophils, and basophils) and nongranular leukocytes (lymphocytes and monocytes), along with red blood cells and platelets. Each cell type has distinct morphology and functions in immunity and blood clotting.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-4": (
    caption: [The stages of erythropoiesis. The proliferation and differentiation of cells that will become mature erythrocytes (red blood cells) occurs in the bone marrow and is stimulated by the hormone erythropoietin (EPO). The process shows progression from hematopoietic stem cells through various stages including proerythroblast, erythroblast, normoblast, reticulocyte, and finally mature erythrocyte.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-5": (
    caption: [Agglutination reaction. People with type A blood have type A antigens on their red blood cells and antibodies in their plasma against the type B antigen. People with type B blood have type B antigens on their red blood cells and antibodies against the type A antigen. The diagram illustrates the immune reaction that occurs when incompatible blood types are mixed.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-6": (
    caption: [Blood typing. Agglutination (clumping) of red blood cells occurs when cells with A-type antigens are mixed with anti-A antibodies and when cells with B-type antigens are mixed with anti-B antibodies. The figure demonstrates the test procedure for determining ABO blood types, showing positive and negative reactions for different blood type samples.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-7": (
    caption: [Platelet aggregation. (a) Platelet aggregation is prevented in an intact endothelium because it separates the blood from collagen, a potential platelet activator. The endothelium also secretes nitric oxide (NO) and prostacyclin (PGI₂), which inhibit platelet activation. (b) When the endothelium is damaged, platelets adhere to collagen and release ADP, which promotes further platelet aggregation and the formation of a platelet plug.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-8": (
    caption: [Colorized scanning electron micrograph of a blood clot. The threads of fibrin have been colored green, the erythrocytes are shown red, and the platelets have been colored purple. This image shows the three-dimensional network structure that forms during blood clotting.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-9": (
    caption: [The clotting pathways. (1) The extrinsic clotting pathway is initiated by the release of tissue factor from damaged tissue. (2) The intrinsic clotting pathway is initiated by the activation of factor XII by contact with collagen or other negatively charged surfaces. Both pathways converge at the activation of factor X, leading to the common pathway that produces thrombin and ultimately fibrin. The diagram shows the cascade of enzymatic reactions and the role of calcium ions and vitamin K-dependent factors.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-10": (
    caption: [A diagram of the circulatory system. The systemic circulation includes the aorta and venae cavae, delivering oxygenated blood to body tissues and returning deoxygenated blood to the heart. The pulmonary circulation includes the pulmonary arteries (carrying deoxygenated blood to the lungs) and pulmonary veins (returning oxygenated blood to the heart). This shows the dual-circuit organization of the cardiovascular system.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-11": (
    caption: [The heart valves. (a) A superior view of the heart valves showing the two atrioventricular (AV) valves (tricuspid and mitral/bicuspid) and the two semilunar valves (pulmonary and aortic). (b) A sagittal section through the heart, showing both AV valves and the pulmonary semilunar valve in their anatomical positions, demonstrating how they prevent backflow of blood.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-12": (
    caption: [A photograph of the aortic and pulmonary semilunar valves. The valve flaps (cusps) are shown in their closed position, demonstrating how they prevent backflow of blood from the aorta and pulmonary artery into the ventricles during diastole.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-13": (
    caption: [Routine stethoscope positions for listening to the heart sounds. The first heart sound (S₁ or "lub") is caused by closing of the AV valves at the beginning of ventricular systole. The second heart sound (S₂ or "dup") is caused by closing of the semilunar valves at the beginning of ventricular diastole. The diagram shows optimal positions for auscultation of each valve.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-14": (
    caption: [Abnormal blood flow due to septal defects. Left-to-right shunting of blood is shown (circled areas) because the left pump is at a higher pressure than the right pump in the adult heart. (a) Leakage of blood through a ventricular septal defect. (b) Leakage of blood through an atrial septal defect. These congenital heart defects allow mixing of oxygenated and deoxygenated blood.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-15": (
    caption: [The flow of blood through a patent (open) ductus arteriosus. The ductus arteriosus is normally open in a fetus but closes after birth, eventually becoming the ligamentum arteriosum. A patent ductus arteriosus is a congenital defect where this vessel fails to close, causing abnormal blood flow between the aorta (AO) and pulmonary artery (PA).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-16": (
    caption: [The cardiac cycle of ventricular systole and diastole. Contraction of the atria occurs in the last 0.1 second of ventricular diastole, helping to fill the ventricles. Relaxation of the atria occurs during ventricular systole. The duration of systole decreases more than the duration of diastole as the cardiac rate increases, demonstrating the phases of the cardiac cycle including atrial contraction, isovolumetric contraction, ejection, isovolumetric relaxation, and ventricular filling.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-17": (
    caption: [The relationship between heart sounds and the intraventricular pressure and volume. The graph correlates heart sounds (S₁ and S₂) with changes in ventricular pressure and volume during the cardiac cycle. The numbers refer to specific events: (1) closing of AV valves, (2) opening of semilunar valves, (3) closing of semilunar valves, (4) opening of AV valves. The diagram shows how pressure changes drive valve opening and closing.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-18": (
    caption: [Pacemaker potentials and action potentials in the SA node. The pacemaker potentials are spontaneous depolarizations caused by a decrease in potassium permeability and an increase in sodium and calcium permeability. When they reach threshold (-40 mV), they trigger action potentials. This automaticity allows the SA node to serve as the heart's natural pacemaker.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-19": (
    caption: [An action potential in a myocardial cell from the ventricles. The plateau phase of the action potential is maintained by a slow inward diffusion of calcium ions (Ca²⁺). The cardiac action potential, as a result, is much longer (200-300 ms) than the action potential in skeletal muscle or neurons, preventing tetanic contractions and ensuring proper filling and emptying of the heart chambers.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-20": (
    caption: [The conduction system of the heart. The conduction system consists of specialized myocardial cells that rapidly conduct electrical impulses from the atria into the ventricles. The pathway includes the sinoatrial (SA) node, atrioventricular (AV) node, bundle of His (AV bundle), right and left bundle branches, and Purkinje fibers. This system coordinates the sequential contraction of the atria and ventricles.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-21": (
    caption: [Correlation of the myocardial action potential with myocardial contraction. The time course for the myocardial action potential is compared with the duration of contraction. The long action potential with its plateau phase prevents premature relaxation and ensures that the heart muscle has time to contract and eject blood before it can be stimulated again. This long refractory period prevents tetanus in cardiac muscle.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-22": (
    caption: [The ECG and cardiac cycle. (a) The electrocardiogram (ECG) waves and intervals, showing the P wave (atrial depolarization), QRS complex (ventricular depolarization), and T wave (ventricular repolarization). (b) The correlation of the myocardial action potentials, ECG waves, and contraction of the atria and ventricles, demonstrating how electrical events precede and trigger mechanical events in the cardiac cycle.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-23": (
    caption: [The relationship between impulse conduction in the heart and the ECG. The direction of the arrows indicates that depolarization of the ventricles occurs from the inside (endocardium) out (to the epicardium). The sequence shows how the electrical impulse spreads through the heart and generates the characteristic ECG waveforms at different time points during the cardiac cycle.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-24": (
    caption: [The electrocardiograph leads. The placement of the bipolar limb leads (leads I, II, and III) and the exploratory electrode for the unipolar chest leads (V₁-V₆) in an electrocardiogram (ECG). The numbered chest positions correspond to different intercostal spaces and anatomical landmarks. These multiple leads provide different electrical "views" of the heart's activity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-25": (
    caption: [The relationship between changes in intraventricular pressure and the ECG. The QRS wave (representing depolarization of the ventricles) occurs at the beginning of systole and triggers ventricular contraction, whereas the T wave (representing repolarization of the ventricles) occurs at the beginning of diastole. This correlation demonstrates how electrical events control mechanical events in the heart.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-26": (
    caption: [The structure of blood vessels. The figure shows the relative thickness and composition of the three layers (tunicas) in comparable arteries and veins. The tunica intima (endothelium), tunica media (smooth muscle and elastic tissue), and tunica externa (connective tissue) are shown. Arteries have thicker walls and more elastic tissue than veins to withstand higher pressure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-27": (
    caption: [The microcirculation. Metarterioles (arteriovenous anastomoses) provide a path of least resistance between arterioles and venules, allowing blood to bypass capillary beds when necessary. Precapillary sphincter muscles regulate the flow of blood through the capillaries, controlling which tissues receive blood flow based on metabolic needs.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-28": (
    caption: [An electron micrograph of a capillary in the heart. The image shows the thin intercellular channel and the capillary wall, composed of only one cell layer (endothelium). Arrows indicate some of the many pinocytotic vesicles that transport materials across the endothelial cells. This thin structure facilitates efficient exchange of gases, nutrients, and wastes between blood and tissues.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-29": (
    caption: [The action of the one-way venous valves. Contraction of skeletal muscles helps to pump blood toward the heart (the skeletal muscle pump), but the flow of blood away from the heart is prevented by closure of the venous valves. This mechanism is crucial for venous return, especially in the lower extremities where blood must flow against gravity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-30": (
    caption: [A demonstration of venous valves by William Harvey. By blocking venous drainage with a tourniquet, Harvey showed that the blood in the bulged vein was not permitted to move away from the heart, thereby demonstrating the existence of venous valves. This historic experiment helped establish the concept of unidirectional blood flow and circulation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-31": (
    caption: [Atherosclerosis. (a) A photograph of the lumen (cavity) of a human coronary artery that is partially occluded by an atherosclerotic plaque and a thrombus. (b) A diagram of the structure of an atherosclerotic plaque, showing the accumulation of lipids, smooth muscle cells, foam cells (lipid-laden macrophages), and fibrous tissue in the arterial wall. The plaque narrows the lumen and can rupture, leading to thrombosis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-32": (
    caption: [Structure of a lipoprotein. There is a core of nonpolar triglycerides and cholesterol esters coated by proteins (apolipoproteins), phospholipids, and some free cholesterol. Different lipoproteins (chylomicrons, VLDL, LDL, HDL) have different proportions of these components and serve different roles in lipid transport. LDL delivers cholesterol to tissues, while HDL removes cholesterol from tissues.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-33": (
    caption: [Depression of the S-T segment as a result of myocardial ischemia. This ECG abnormality indicates insufficient blood flow and oxygen supply to the heart muscle, often due to coronary artery disease. S-T segment depression or elevation can indicate the location and severity of ischemia or infarction.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-34": (
    caption: [Some arrhythmias detected by the ECG. (a) Normal sinus rhythm where the heartbeat is paced by the SA node. This can be abnormally slow (sinus bradycardia, less than 60 beats per minute) or abnormally fast (sinus tachycardia, greater than 100 beats per minute). (b) Atrial flutter showing rapid, regular atrial contractions. (c) Ventricular tachycardia showing rapid, abnormal ventricular rhythms. These arrhythmias can compromise cardiac output and require medical intervention.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-35": (
    caption: [Atrioventricular (AV) node block. In first-degree block, the P-R interval is greater than 0.20 second, indicating delayed conduction through the AV node. In second-degree block, some P waves are not followed by QRS complexes, meaning some atrial impulses fail to reach the ventricles. In third-degree (complete) block, there is no relationship between P waves and QRS complexes, as the atria and ventricles beat independently.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-36": (
    caption: [The relationship between blood capillaries and lymphatic capillaries. Lymphatic capillaries are blind-ended vessels that are highly permeable to fluid and proteins. Excess fluid and protein that leak from blood capillaries into the interstitial space are collected by lymphatic capillaries and returned to the blood circulation, helping to maintain fluid balance and prevent edema.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-37": (
    caption: [The relationship between the circulatory and lymphatic systems. This schematic illustrates that the lymphatic system transports fluid from the interstitial space back to the blood through a system of lymphatic vessels and lymph nodes. Lymph eventually drains into the subclavian veins, completing the circuit and maintaining cardiovascular homeostasis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "13-38": (
    caption: [The location of lymph nodes along the lymphatic pathways. Lymph nodes are small bean-shaped bodies enclosed within dense connective tissue capsules. They filter lymph, removing pathogens and debris, and are sites where immune responses are initiated. Major lymph node clusters are found in the cervical, axillary, inguinal, and abdominal regions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
)
